Certainly! It sounds like you're dealing with a simple Caesar cipher, where each letter in the message is shifted by a fixed number of positions in the alphabet. To decrypt the message, you'll need to try different shifts until you find the one that produces a meaningful message. Once you have the decrypted message, you can identify and correct any mistakes.

Here's a Java program that attempts all possible shifts (0-25) to decrypt the message:

```java
public class CaesarCipherDecrypt {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String encryptedMessage = "RSTU VWXY ZABC DFGH IJKL MNOP QE";
        decryptMessage(encryptedMessage);
    }

    public static void decryptMessage(String message) {
        for (int shift = 0; shift < 26; shift++) {
            StringBuilder decryptedMessage = new StringBuilder();

            for (char c : message.toCharArray()) {
                if (Character.isLetter(c)) {
                    char shiftedChar = (char) (c - shift);
                    if (shiftedChar < 'A') {
                        shiftedChar += 26;
                    }
                    decryptedMessage.append(shiftedChar);
                } else {
                    decryptedMessage.append(c);
                }
            }

            System.out.println("Shift " + shift + ": " + decryptedMessage);
        }
    }
}
```

This program tries all possible shifts and prints the result for each one. You can manually check the output to identify which shift gives you a readable message.

Once you find the correct decrypted message, you can manually review it for any grammatical or spelling mistakes and correct them as needed.

If you find a specific shift that produces the correct message, you can focus on that shift and correct any mistakes in the resulting text. Let me know if you need further assistance or have found the shift that works!
